ourke Prine\n* ''[[Springfield Rifle (film)|Springfield Rifle]]'' (1952) - Sgt. Snow\n* ''[[Hangman's Knot]]'' (1952) - Smitty\n* ''[[Southwest Passage]]'' (1954) - Tall Tale\n* ''Massacre Canyon'' (1954) - Private Peaceful Allen\n* ''[[The Outlaw's Daughter (film)|The Outlaw's Daughter]]'' (1954) - Moose, Deputy\n* ''[[Hidden Guns]]'' (1956) - Kingford\n* ''[[Man from Del Rio]]'' (1956) - Fred Jasper (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Hired Gun (1957 film)|The Hired Gun]]'' (1957) - Elby Kirby\n* ''[[Home from the Hill (film)|Home from the Hill]]'' (1960) - Hugh Macauley (uncredited)\n* ''Five Bold Women'' (1960) - Big Foot\n* ''[[The Alamo (1960 film)|The Alamo]]'' (1960) - Lt. 'Irish' Finn\n* ''[[The Comancheros (film)|The Comancheros]]'' (1961) - Ed McBain - Gunrunner (final film, uncredited)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Television===\n{{div col}}\n* ''[[My Friend Flicka (TV series)|My Friend Flicka]]'' (1955-1956) - Jeb Taylor \n* ''[[Circus Boy]]'' (1956-1957) - Pete, the Canvasman \n* ''[[Gunsmoke]]'' (1957) - Groat  \n* ''[[Cheyenne (TV series)|Cheyenne]]'' (1957) - Prairie Dog \n* ''[[Sugarfoot]]'' (1958) - Moose McKlintock \n* ''[[The Adventures of Rin Tin Tin]]'' (1958) - Sgt. Muldoon \n* ''[[Tales of Wells Fargo]]'' (1958) - Mike Forbes\n* ''[[Wagon Train]]'' (1959) - Calvin Bryngelson\n* ''[[The Restless Gun]]'' (1959) - Jeff Bonsell \n* ''[[Walt Disney anthology television series|The Magical World of Disney]]'' (1960) - Buffalo\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0930711}}\n* {{Amg name|76454}}\n* [http://www.b-westerns.com/bigboy.htm Guinn \"Big Boy\" Williams full biography]\n* {{Find a Grave|6080139}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Guinn}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Texas]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male silent film actors]]\n[[Category:People from Decatur, Texas]]\n[[Category:Male Western (genre) film actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:Texas Democrats]]\n[[Category:American Methodists]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2016}}\n\n{{infobox person\n| name             = Guinn \"Big Boy\" Williams\n| image            = Poster of the movie The Law of 45's.jpg\n| caption          = Guinn Williams, in ''[[The Law of the 45's]]'' (1935)\n| birth_name       = Guinn Terrell Williams Jr.\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1899|04|26}}\n| birth_place      = [[Decatur, Texas]], U.S.\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1962|06|06|1899|04|26}}\n| death_place      = [[Hollywood, California]], U.S.\n| occupation       = Actor\n| years_active     = 1919&ndash;1961\n| spouse           = [[Barbara Weeks (film actress)|Barbara Weeks]]<br>({{abbr|m.|married}} 19??; {{abbr|div.|divorced}} 19??) <br/>Kathleen Collins<br>({{abbr|m.|married}} 19??; {{abbr|div.|divorced}} 19??)<br/>{{marriage|[[Dorothy Peterson]]<br>|1943}}\n| other_names      = Big Boy\n}}\n[[File:DANGER TRAILS poster.jpg|thumb]]\n[[File:Santa Fe Trail 2.jpg|thumb|''[[Santa Fe Trail (film)|Santa Fe Trail]]''  - L. to R. : Guinn 'Big Boy' Williams, Alan Hale (Sr.), Ronald Reagan, and Errol Flynn]]\n\n'''Guinn Terrell Williams Jr.''' (April 26, 1899 &ndash; June 6, 1962) was an [[United States|American]] actor who appeared in memorable [[western (genre)|western]]s such as ''[[Dodge City (film)|Dodge City]]'' (1939), ''[[Santa Fe Trail (film)|Santa Fe Trail]]'' (1940), and ''[[The Comancheros (film)|The Comancheros]]'' (1961). He was nicknamed \"Big Boy\" as he was 6' 2\" and had a muscular build from years of working on ranches and playing semi-pro and professional baseball.\n\n==Biography==\nHis father, [[Guinn Williams]] (1871-1948), a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] congressman, represented the [[United States House of Representatives, Texas District 13|13th Texas Congressional District]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]] from 1922 to 1932.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=W000501|title=WILLIAMS, Guinn - Biographical Information|website=bioguide.congress.gov}}</ref> When Williams Jr. returned from [[World War I]] as an Army officer, he found out his father had secured for him an appointment to [[West Point]] that Williams Jr. saw no need to attend after his war service; he decided to become a baseball player instead.  He was introduced by [[Will Rogers]] into motion pictures and polo, where he became a champion player and was given the name \"Big Boy\" by Rogers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://smmercury.com/2012/08/23/bartee-haile-big-boy-williams-has-eerie-premonition-of-his-death/ |title=Bartee Haile: 'Big boy' Williams has eerie premonition of his death |date=August 23, 2012 |accessdate=November 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWilliams made his screen debut in the 1919 comedy, ''Almost A Husband'', with Will Rogers and [[Cullen Landis]], and was featured in a large supporting role ten years later in [[Frank Borzage]]'s ''[[Lucky Star (1929 film)|Lucky Star]]'' with [[Janet Gaynor]] and [[Charles Farrell]]. Throughout the 1920s, Williams would have a string of successful films, mostly westerns.\n\nHe then appeared in ''[[The Great Meadow]]'' alongside [[Johnny Mack Brown]], which was Brown's breakout film. Throughout the 1930s, Williams acted in supporting roles, mostly in westerns, sports, or outdoor dramas. He was always employed, and was successful as both a B picture leading man and a supporting actor in A pictures. He often played alongside [[Hoot Gibson]] and [[Harry Carey (actor)|Harry Carey]] during that period. In 1941, he became one of many actors cast by [[Universal Pictures]] in their large film series, ''[[Riders of Death Valley]]''. From the late 1930s to the mid-1940s, Williams appeared in supporting roles in a number of A-pictures, sometimes with high billing, such as ''You Only Live Once'', and in Columbia's first Technicolor film, ''[[The Desperadoes]]'' (1943).\n\nWilliams was frequently teamed with [[Alan Hale, Sr.]] as sidekicks to [[Errol Flynn]] in several of his pictures. In 1960, he was cast in the [[epic film]] ''[[The Alamo (1960 film)|The Alamo]]'' and in ''[[Home from the Hill (film)|Home from the Hill]]'' with [[Robert Mitchum]]. His last role was opposite his close friend [[John Wayne]] and [[Stuart Whitman]] in ''[[The Comancheros (film)|The Comancheros]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\n\nHe was married to three actresses, the first being silent film actress Kathleen Collins. For a time, he was married to [[B-movie]] actress [[Barbara Weeks (film actress)|Barbara Weeks]]. His last wife was Dorothy Peterson, whom he first met in the 1940s. Prior to meeting her he had been engaged to [[Lupe Velez]] but she literally broke off the engagement at their friend [[Errol Flynn]]'s home by breaking a framed portrait of Williams over his head<ref>pp. 192-193 Vogel, Michelle ''Lupe Velez: The Life and Career of Hollywood's Mexican Spitfire'' McFarland, 2012</ref> and then urinating on the picture.<ref>p.297 Flynn, Erroll ''My Wicked, Wicked Ways'' Aurum Press, 2002</ref>\n\nLike his father, Williams was active in an array of notable and state related causes. He worked with the regional Agricultural Credit Association, The Production Credit Corporation, The Goat Raisers Association, The Texas Wool and Mohair Company, and the Bankers Association (all of which coincided both in his native Texas and adopted California). Throughout his life Williams was active both in community affairs and the [[Methodist]] churches of Decatur, Texas, San Angelo, Texas, and Los Angeles, California.<ref>Morning News, January 10, 1948, ''Who Was Who in America'' (Vol. 2).</ref>\n\nWilliams died unexpectedly of [[Acute kidney injury|uremic poisoning]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b-westerns.com/bigboy4.htm|title=Guinn 'Big Boy' Williams|website=www.b-westerns.com}}</ref> on June 6, 1962, aged 63.\n\n==Filmography==\n{{div col}}\n* ''[[Almost a Husband]]'' (1919) - (film debut)\n* ''[[Jubilo]]'' (1919) - Man Shooting Pool with Bert (uncredited)\n* ''[[Cupid the Cowpuncher]]'' (1920) - Hairoil Johnson\n* ''[[Godless Men]]'' (1920) - Seaman (uncredited)\n* ''The Vengeance Trail'' (1921) - Big Boy Bronson\n* ''Western Firebrands'' (1921) - Billy Fargo\n* ''Across the Border'' (1922) - Andy Fowler\n* ''[[Rounding Up the Law (1922 film)|Rounding Up the Law]]'' (1922) - Larry Connell\n* ''The Cowboy King'' (1922) - Dud Smiley\n* ''[[Remembrance (1922 film)|Remembrance]]'' (1922)\n* ''[[The Trail of Hate (1922 film)|The Trail of Hate]]'' (1922) - Silent Kerry\n* ''Blaze Away'' (1922) - Big Boy\n* ''The Freshie'' (1922) - Charles Taylor\n* ''Cyclone Jones'' (1923) - Cyclone Jones\n* ''Riders at Night'' (1923)\n* ''End of the Rope'' (1923)\n* ''$1,000 Reward'' (1923)\n* ''The Avenger'' (1924) - Nat Sherwood\n* ''[[The Eagle's Claw]]'' (1924) - Dan Carson\n* ''Red Blood and Blue'' (1925) - Tom Butler\n* ''Fangs of Wolfheart'' (1925)\n* ''Wolfheart's Revenge'' (1925) - Jack Stanley\n* ''Sporting West'' (1925)\n* ''Black Cyclone'' (1925) - Jim Lawson\n* ''Whistling Jim'' (1925) - Whistling Jim\n* ''Rose of the Desert'' (1925)\n* ''Riders of the Sand Storm'' (1925) - The Cowboy\n* ''Courage of Wolfheart'' (1925)\n* ''The Big Stunt'' (1925)\n* ''[[Brown of Harvard (1926 film)|Brown of Harvard]]'' (1926) - Hal Walters\n* ''[[The Desert's Toll]]'' (1926)\n* ''Quarantined Rivals'' (1927) - Joe, the plumber\n* ''[[Slide, Kelly, Slide]]'' (1927) - McLean\n* ''Backstage'' (1927) - Mike Donovan\n* ''[[Arizona Bound (1927 film)|Arizona Bound]]'' (1927) - Cowboy\n* ''[[Snowbound (1927 film)|Snowbound]]'' (1927) - Bull Morgan\n* ''[[Babe Comes Home]]'' (1927) - Baseball Player\n* ''[[The Woman Who Did Not Care]]'' (1927) - Lars\n* ''Lightning'' (1927) - Cuth St